04143nam a2200661Ia 9781501721809DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017218097 a10.7591/97815017218092doi  a(DE-B1597)515314  a(OCoLC)1088909535  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDU624.65b.I76 1999 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306/.099692211 aIto, Karen L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLady Friends :bHawaiian Ways and the Ties that Define /cKaren L. Ito. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Anthropology of Contemporary Issues00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Lady Friends and Their Island Home -- t2. Comeback and the Ties That Bind -- t3. "My Heart Is in My Friend": The Ties That Define -- t4. Ho'oponopono and Conflict Resolution -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany indigenous Hawaiians who have moved to the islands' cities languish at the bottom of the socioeconomic scale and are thought to have lost their cultural roots. Initially apolitical urban Hawaiians were often skeptical of activists who sought to revitalize traditional ways; yet, as Karen L. Ito shows, Hawaiian women in particular continue to maintain and express crucial aspects of their cultural heritage in their lifestyle and interactions with others. Ito conducted intensive fieldwork with six Honolulu families, all of which shared the distinguishing characteristics of Hawaii's matrifocal society. In her close examination of the friendships and family relations among the women in these households, she focuses on the significance of a traditional manner of speech known as "talk story" which they use when conversing together. She describes how her subjects employ metaphoric language to address issues concerning responsibility, retribution, understandings of self and personhood, and methods for conflict resolution. For these "lady friends," Ito finds, the emotional quality and quantity of their social relationships help define personal identity while their common concepts of morality bind them together. By applying ethnopsychological strategies to the exploration of culture, Ito demonstrates cultural continuity at a level where most observers would not expect to find it. Lady Friends brings a new dimension to Hawaiian research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHawaiian women. 0aHawaiiansxEthnic identity. 0aHawaiiansxSocial life and customs. 4aAnthropology. 4aGender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172180940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501721809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501721809/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles